          SEC Space SPACIn November 2019, a special purpose acquisition com=
pany called Stable Road Acquisition Corp. went public, raising $172.5=C2=A0=
million from investors to merge with a company to be named later. Specifica=
lly, according to the first paragraph of its prospectus, Stable Road was lo=
oking =E2=80=9Cto focus our search on companies in the cannabis industry wh=
ich are compliant with all applicable laws and regulations.=E2=80=9D It had=
 18 months to find one; if it failed, it had to give investors their $150 m=
illion back.After considering =E2=80=9Cdozens of companies in that industry=
,=E2=80=9D Stable Road decided not to buy a cannabis company, and by June 2=
020 it was casting its net more widely. Specifically in outer space. That m=
onth, Stable Road=E2=80=99s sponsor Brian Kabot met Mikhail Kokorich, the f=
ounder of a company called Momentus Inc., which makes plasma space rockets,=
 or tries=C2=A0to anyway:Large commercial satellite launch providers offer =
launch services to satellite owners but only leave these =E2=80=9Crideshare=
=E2=80=9D satellites in a limited range of orbits. Momentus hopes to=C2=A0o=
ffer =E2=80=9Clast mile=E2=80=9D satellite placement services to place thes=
e rideshare satellites into custom orbits of the customers=E2=80=99 choosin=
g. According to Momentus=E2=80=99s plans, Momentus will integrate its custo=
mer=E2=80=99s payload into Momentus=E2=80=99s vehicle, which will then be l=
oaded onto a larger rocket. The rocket will then leave Momentus=E2=80=99s v=
ehicle in orbit, at which point Momentus will move its vehicle and the cust=
omer=E2=80=99s integrated payload into a custom orbit using what it touted =
in investor presentations as its =E2=80=9Ccornerstone=E2=80=9D technology, =
a propulsion system using MET water plasma thrusters.Cool! That is not obvi=
ously connected to cannabis, but nor is it obviously=C2=A0not=C2=A0connecte=
d to cannabis I guess.Anyway Kokorich talked a good game about his plasma s=
pace rockets, and Kabot had $172.5 million burning a hole in his pocket, so=
 a deal was struck. =E2=80=9CSRAC engaged several firms to assist with due =
diligence, including a space technology consulting firm with the expertise =
to investigate the state of development of Momentus=E2=80=99s technology=E2=
=80=9D; apparently the space technology consulting firm (cool!) declared Mo=
mentus=E2=80=99s technology good. So Kokorich and Kabot negotiated a merger=
 agreement, and they also pitched other investors on a PIPE (private invest=
ment in public equity) to buy another $175 million of Momentus stock alongs=
ide the SPAC merger. The deal was announced in October 2020.Yesterday the U=
.S. Securities and Exchange Commission sued Momentus, Stable Road, Kokorich=
 and Kabot, claiming that Kokorich was lying to Kabot, and that Kabot passe=
d along those lies to investors. Everyone but Kokorich settled, agreeing to=
 pay a total of $8 million to the SEC, forfeit some founders=E2=80=99 share=
s in the SPAC,=C2=A0and let the PIPE investors get their money back if they=
 want to.There are two main categories of alleged lies. One is about the pl=
asma space rockets. Specifically, in July 2019 Momentus sent a plasma space=
 rocket up into space to test it out, and it basically didn=E2=80=99t work,=
 but Momentus told everyone that it did. I=E2=80=99m going to block quote f=
rom the SEC=E2=80=99s order here, not so much because it adds much to the s=
tory but because there are a lot of cool space words:The El Camino Real mis=
sion did not meet any of the public or internal success criteria. After exp=
eriencing significant issues with supporting sub-systems and its propulsion=
 system, Momentus achieved only twelve =E2=80=9Chot firings=E2=80=9D with m=
icrowave power turned on out of 23 firings. While a pump issue significantl=
y restricted flow of water into the thruster during nine of the 12 hot firi=
ngs, preventing plasma-generation, data suggests that only three hot firing=
s produced plasma. However, none of the firings lasted a full minute and no=
ne generated measurable thrust. Momentus lost contact with the satellite ap=
proximately three months into the planned six-month mission and was never a=
ble to attempt the remaining 77 firings it had planned, much less achieve a=
ny of the =E2=80=9C100 individual burns of 1 minute or more.=E2=80=9DThe El=
 Camino Real satellite is still in space, but it is not functional.The El C=
amino Real mission did not demonstrate the thruster=E2=80=99s ability to pr=
ovide commercial launch services. The mission yielded no data to suggest th=
at the 2019 version of the thruster would deliver an impulse of any commerc=
ial significance, failed to demonstrate the propulsion system=E2=80=99s rel=
iability of longevity, and did not characterize the performance of the thru=
sters.Cool, okay. But Kokorich allegedly lied about the success of the miss=
ion in an interview in Space News, cool:In a September 25, 2019 article in =
Space News titled, =E2=80=9CMomentus reports success in testing water plasm=
a propulsion,=E2=80=9D Kokorich enthused, after testing had begun on the El=
 Camino Real mission, =E2=80=9CWater plasma propulsion is now technological=
ly mature enough to be baselined for operational in-space transportation mi=
ssions.=E2=80=9D He also repeated the claim from Momentus=E2=80=99s January=
 2019 blog post that =E2=80=9Cthe purpose of the El Camino Real mission was=
 to flight demonstrate our core propulsion technology so customers, investo=
rs and stakeholders can have absolute confidence that Momentus will deliver=
 their payloads to a given orbit.=E2=80=9DSome versions of these alleged li=
es also made it into the slide presentation that Momentus and Stable Road m=
ade to potential PIPE investors, and=C2=A0into the original proxy statement=
/prospectus that Stable Road published after announcing the merger, the dis=
closure document that it prepared for SPAC investors to consider whether to=
 approve the deal.[1] That document, incidentally, came out in November 202=
0; there has still been no shareholder vote on the deal, and the most recen=
t revised proxy/prospectus, dated this Monday, contains more accurate discl=
osure about the El Camino Real test satellite.[2]The other alleged lies wer=
e about Kokorich=E2=80=99s immigration status and, uh, national-security st=
atus? Kokorich is Russian and, =E2=80=9Cbecause Kokorich is a foreign natio=
nal, he could not access parts of Momentus=E2=80=99s technology without an =
export license.=E2=80=9D Momentus applied for that license and it was denie=
d, =E2=80=9Cfor reasons related to national security.=E2=80=9D Also he was =
in the U.S. on a work visa, and in 2018 his visa was revoked. He applied fo=
r asylum and that was also denied. In January 2021 =E2=80=94=C2=A0after the=
 merger was signed and announced =E2=80=94=C2=A0he stepped down as CEO of M=
omentus and left the U.S.; he currently lives in=C2=A0Switzerland. Momentus=
 is still under a bit of a national-security cloud; Kokorich has agreed to =
divest all his Momentus shares, and Momentus has agreed =E2=80=9Cto impleme=
nt increased security measures and appoint a CFIUS-approved director to its=
 board of directors,=E2=80=9D so that it can get U.S. government approval t=
o launch satellites. But, according to the SEC, =E2=80=9CMomentus and Kokor=
ich did not share the extent of Kokorich=E2=80=99s national security issues=
 with SRAC and Kabot,=E2=80=9D and the original proxy/prospectus expressed =
more optimism about Kokorich staying in the U.S. and remaining CEO of Momen=
tus than was justified by the facts.This is as far as I can tell the first =
SEC securities-fraud case from the current SPAC boom. It won=E2=80=99t be t=
he last. The SEC has made it clear that it has  no love for SPACs, and that=
 it is going to=C2=A0 enforce=C2=A0the letter of the law against SPACs. The=
re are other companies that have done SPAC mergers=C2=A0and then,=C2=A0uh, =
 admitted to making false statements to investors? Presumably those will be=
 of interest to the SEC?=C2=A0But the Momentus case shows how weird SEC SPA=
C enforcement is going to be. For instance here is a strange little questio=
n: Who was harmed by Momentus=E2=80=99s alleged lies? Obvious answers might=
 include =E2=80=9CStable Road,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CStable Road=E2=80=99s p=
ublic shareholders,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cthe PIPE investors=E2=80=9D: Momen=
tus allegedly lied about its technology and its CEO=E2=80=99s immigration s=
tatus, causing Stable Road and the PIPE investors to agree to overpay for i=
ts stock. Fine. But the SEC is going after Stable Road=E2=80=99s sponsors=
=C2=A0too, for being lied to, and for not catching the lies. And reasonably=
 enough. The SEC=E2=80=99s press release says:=E2=80=9CThis case illustrate=
s risks inherent to SPAC transactions, as those who stand to earn significa=
nt profits from a SPAC merger may conduct inadequate due diligence and misl=
ead investors,=E2=80=9D said SEC Chair Gary Gensler. =E2=80=9CStable Road, =
a SPAC, and its merger target, Momentus, both misled the investing public. =
The fact that Momentus lied to Stable Road does not absolve Stable Road of =
its failure to undertake adequate due diligence to protect shareholders. To=
day=E2=80=99s actions will prevent the wrongdoers from benefitting at the e=
xpense of investors and help to better align the incentives of parties to a=
 SPAC transaction with those of investors relying on truthful information t=
o make investment decisions.=E2=80=9DIf you sponsor a SPAC, you are to some=
 extent just a conduit, a service provider connecting public investors who =
want a company with a company that wants public investors. But you have to =
provide the service! And that includes doing some due diligence on the comp=
any you=E2=80=99re acquiring, to make sure that it isn=E2=80=99t selling li=
es to your investors.In any case, though,=C2=A0the lies were eventually dis=
covered =E2=80=94=C2=A0perhaps through the SEC=E2=80=99s intervention, perh=
aps not =E2=80=94=C2=A0and last month the merger agreement was amended to r=
educe the price. The most recent amended proxy/prospectus explains (page 30=
) that the merger agreement was amended on June 29; the amendment, =E2=80=
=9Camong other things, =E2=80=A6=C2=A0reduced the enterprise value of Momen=
tus from $1.131 billion to $566.6 million.=E2=80=9D They cut the price in h=
alf to account for Momentus=E2=80=99s various troubles. The deal hasn=E2=80=
=99t closed yet, and the SPAC=E2=80=99s shareholders could still vote it do=
wn (or get their money back)=C2=A0if they don=E2=80=99t like what they read=
 in the new proxy/prospectus or the SEC order. Momentus allegedly lied abou=
t its business to sell stock, but it hasn=E2=80=99t actually sold any stock=
 yet. The SEC=E2=80=99s press release says:=E2=80=9COur enforcement team wo=
rked with incredible speed, efficiency, and creativity to file today=E2=80=
=99s actions so that investors will have the benefit of complete and accura=
te information when voting on the proposed merger,=E2=80=9D said Melissa R.=
 Hodgman, Acting Director of the SEC=E2=80=99s Division of Enforcement.=C2=
=A0So everything=E2=80=99s fine! Now you might object that that=E2=80=99s n=
o defense, there=E2=80=99s no =E2=80=9Cno harm no foul=E2=80=9D defense to =
securities fraud, and even attempting to sell stock by lies is illegal. But=
 there=E2=80=99s a more important objection, which is that Momentus may not=
 have sold any stock yet, but people sure have=C2=A0bought=C2=A0stock. Beca=
use remember that, while all of this was going on, Stable Road=E2=80=99s st=
ock traded publicly on the stock exchange. It sold stock, at $10 per share,=
 as a blank-check company back in November 2019. And then, as a pool of mon=
ey hunting for a deal, it traded at around $10 per share. When it announced=
 a merger with a cool space company, its stock went up. Cool space company!=
 Successfully tested its plasma rockets in space! CEO probably wasn=E2=80=
=99t getting deported! The stock closed as high as $27.42 per share this Fe=
bruary.[3] Then much of that enthusiasm drained away; the stock closed at $=
11.88 yesterday.[4]=C2=A0Everyone who bought Stable Road stock between the =
announcement of the merger (November 2020) and, let=E2=80=99s say, Monday (=
the most recent revised proxy/prospectus) has some claim that they were dec=
eived by Momentus=E2=80=99s alleged lies, that they overpaid for Stable Roa=
d stock because (1) they expected it to transform into Momentus stock when =
the merger closed and (2) they thought Momentus was better than it was. The=
 fact that Momentus and Stable Road=C2=A0corrected=C2=A0those alleged lies =
before the merger closed, and before Momentus sold any stock, isn=E2=80=99t=
 good enough: Even before the deal closed, Stable Road=E2=80=99s stock trad=
ed on the stock exchange, and its price moved based on what Momentus=E2=80=
=99s and Stable Road=E2=80=99s statements=C2=A0about Momentus=E2=80=99s bus=
iness. If those statements were wrong, there are going to be aggrieved shar=
eholders, even if they are not technically Momentus=C2=A0shareholders yet.S=
audi! Arabia! Green! Bond!Saudi=C2=A0Arabia green bond!Saudi Arabia's Publi=
c Investment Fund (PIF) is considering its first issuance of green bonds by=
 the fourth quarter of 2021, CNBC Arabia reported, citing banking sources.T=
he issuance comes as part of the fund's plan of shifting towards injecting =
liquidity into environment-friendly investments, the sources said.They adde=
d that the fund is set to hire global investment banks to set the framework=
 for its move towards green investment.Saudi Arabia green bond! Look! I am =
sure you can do green projects in Saudi Arabia. They have a lot of land and=
 sunshine, solar panels, why not. I am sure that the Saudi government =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0or its government-controlled Public Investment Fund =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0can do those green projects. I am sure that there are bond investors =
who are looking for both (1) Saudi Arabia exposure (a good credit, due to a=
ll its oil wealth!) and also (2) green-bond exposure. I am sure they will b=
uy Saudi Arabian green bonds. And why not? It=E2=80=99s a good story, right=
? =E2=80=9CAnyone can buy green bonds of countries=C2=A0without=C2=A0massiv=
e oil resources, but by buying=C2=A0Saudi Arabian=C2=A0green bonds we are a=
ctually pushing a major oil producer=C2=A0in the direction of sustainabilit=
y, of drilling less oil and installing more solar panels,=E2=80=9D you can =
tell yourself, why not, why not, why not. I am sure oil companies issue gre=
en bonds, why not, why not, why not.Environmental, social and governance in=
vesting=C2=A0is amazing. I feel like the first thing you learn about stock =
investing is that it is not sufficient to buy good companies and avoid bad =
companies; everything is judged not in absolute terms but relative to marke=
t expectations. You want to buy bad companies that are better than everyone=
 thinks, and sell good companies that aren=E2=80=99t as good as everyone th=
inks, etc. The business of investing is=C2=A0  necessarily=C2=A0contrarian;=
 everything you do is about figuring out where your views differ from marke=
t consensus.=C2=A0None of that quite makes sense if you apply it to ESG inv=
esting, but if you get enough people whose entire business is about contrar=
ianism, about avoiding obvious trades and looking for undervalued diamonds =
in the rough, I guess some of them will buy Saudi green bonds?Also I have n=
ot even mentioned how Saudi Arabia=E2=80=99s absolute rulers sometimes kidn=
ap their critics abroad, torture them to death and then dismember them, whi=
ch probably costs it some ESG points. But not that many ESG points!


