rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> more tax-efficient</a> than buyin=
g an index fund.) But the real magic here is if you want to buy everything =
in the S&amp;P 500=C2=A0<em>except=C2=A0</em>Tesla, because you don=E2=80=
=99t like Elon Musk, or=C2=A0<em>except </em>oil companies, because you hav=
e environmental commitments, or whatever. Vanguard and BlackRock and others=
 will offer index and quasi-index funds to cater to various sorts of non-in=
dex-y commitments, but not=C2=A0<em>every possible combination=C2=A0</em>of=
 commitments. So if you have idiosyncratic views, you might want to own the=
 stocks yourself.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still it is=C2=A0<em>hard=
er=C2=A0</em>than buying an index fund or ETF, just administratively; you h=
ave to figure out how much of each stock to buy and hit the buttons and so =
forth. But obviously companies are working on automating that. And Vanguard=
, sensibly, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/244487=
